item.caption: Patient Instructions - Walker, Drew, M.D. - Mon Feb 16, 2015 11:59 PM CST
item.paragraph:
Patient Information on Allergies and Asthma
You have been diagnosed with asthma and allergies. These conditions are quite common, and there are lots of things you can do to keep your allergies from flaring up.
What are allergies?
Allergies are caused by your immune system overreacting to things that are harmless to other people, like cat hair, mold, pollen, and house dust. Common reactions include sneezing, runny nose, itchy throat, wheezing, and rashes.
How can I avoid these reactions?
1. Avoid things that trigger your allergies. Keep windows up during days with a high pollen count if you are allergic to pollens. Use air purifiers and air conditioners.
2. Take your medications. You doctor may have prescribed medications for you to take every day. Certain medications work to prevent allergic flare ups and must be taken regularly. If they are only taken after you are not feeling well, they do not do their job.
3. Keep stress levels down. Allergic reactions are often worse when accompanied by stress.

item.caption: Carter, Janell - Mon Feb 16, 2015 10:25 AM CST
item.paragraph: Mild problems with managing allergies, but nothing significant.

td.paragraph:
AT ANY TIME, CALL YOUR MEDICAL PROVIDER IF:
· Asthma symptoms worsen while you are taking oral steroids, or
· Quick-relief medication is lasting less than 4 hours, or
· Your peak flow number falls below 50% of personal best despite following your Asthma Action Plan.
YELLOW ZONE: Asthma is Getting Worse
· Cough, wheeze, chest tightness or shortness of breath, or
· Waking at night due to asthma, or
· Can do some, but not all, usual activities
Take the Following Actions:
Add: Quick-Relief Medicine
First: Take 2 puffs of your quick-relief medicine every 30 minutes.
Then: If your symptoms (and peak flows) return to Green Zone after 1 hour of above treatment: Take 2 puffs of your quick-relief medicine every 4 hours. If your symptoms (and peak flows) do not return to Green Zone after 1 hour of above treatment: Take 2 puffs of your quick-relief medicine every 30 minutes.
RED ZONE: Medical Alert!
· Very short of breath, or
· Quick relief medications have not helped, or
· Cannot do usual activities, or
· Symptoms are same or worse after 24 hours in the Yellow Zone
Take the Following Actions:
First: Take 2 puffs of your quick-relief medicine every 10 minutes.
Then call your medical provider NOW.

Negative for intraepithelial lesion or malignancy.
COMMENT: Cervical cytology is a screening test with limited
sensitivity. It is not a diagnostic procedure and should not be
used as the sole means to detect cervical cancer, especially in
patients with symptoms or an abnormal cervix. Regular screening
is critical for cancer prevention. Cervical cytology tests are
primarily effective for the diagnosis/prevention of squamous cell
carcinoma, not adenocarcinoma or other malignancies.
